\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Don\rquote 
t go too far ahead! For instance, about the Jewish community. Was there an intellectual strand in that, that you were in touch with when you were younger?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Intellectual strand? Well ... not seriously, no ...No, I don\rquote t think so. But I didn\rquote 
t find anything in the formal Jewish religion, the part I heard at synagogue, which I broke from when I was about 14 or 15, very edifying you know, I just decided that one day I would just not go to synagogue anymore. I didn\rquote 
t believe it, and I decided I was an atheist, and that was it. I don\rquote t think ... from that formal tradition, I don\rquote t think I got a great deal ... well, except, again, you know, the great words, the Biblically resonant words of \'93justice
\'94 and \'93mercy\'94. And, you know, I think kids who don\rquote t get religion are not exposed to concepts like atonement, and justice and mercy, and these big ideas. They miss something so I must have got something from that. But more from the
 Youth Movement. And through the Youth Movement, being led into literature which was more interesting, yes. Not necessarily Jewish, but certainly a kindred literature ... I suppose a literature of marginality, I got introduced to then, even before I went 
to university, of people who were sort of on the edge of society.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 What about your relationship with your parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I think ... I think things changed. I think that\rquote s why I mark going to university as }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 break. You know, because everythin
g before that was either negative influences or the puzzles that I talked about. But once I\rquote 
d made that commitment to go, that I was going to university, and that I was going to be an activist at some level, and the level was by doing social work, I think everything else then started changing dramatically. So that\rquote 
s why I think I would go to that level to answer all your other questions. I think ... those were just marvellous four years for me. I don\rquote t think I\rquote ve ever had four better years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So you\rquote d best talk about university, and then come back? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yes. But ... yes, I think it was there that ... 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 This is the university in Johannesburg? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yeah, University of Witwatersrand, in Johannesburg. \'93Wits\'94 as it\rquote 
s known, yes. And there, I [was] ... firstly, away from the ... the numbing boredom of school, and the cadets and the sport and everything ... I just found myself in an environment where all these little bits of identities seemed to be available. You know
,
 I was reading a lot, I was involved in the Jewish part ... I think I was Chairman of the Student Jewish Association in my second or third year. But most important of all, I was learning. I was getting exposed to sociology, to the social sciences, because
 part of doing social work was an Introduction to Sociology, which was not very good, but it certainly got me into the social sciences! 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
But above all, it was going there at a political time. 1958, \rquote 59 were crucial years. This was when the so-called \'93Extension of Universities Act\'94
, which shut the universities down to blacks, began, and there were immediate protests on the campus. And I was drawn to these, absolutely instinctively, and I knew that\rquote s where I belonged. And I think that\rquote s where, you know }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 going back to relationships with my parents}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 , that's where ... you know, I started being different, and saw the difficulty of that. And I eventually ended up just by not telling them. They always worried about that, you know, that I would be arrested, and there
 was always that atmosphere of tension and disapproval from them. Not that I was really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 doing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 very much, but those were years where participation in campus politics was quite a significant way into other political commitment. 
