t possibly celebrate apartheid, and join in with this rally\'94. Which was going
 to be in Bloemfontein, if I remember, which was the heart of apartheid South Africa. That was a dramatic break for me. And we were ... I was very conscious, and I left the Movement, you know, I said, \'93I\rquote 
m just not going to continue in the Movement then\'94. Because they said we mustn\rquote t make a fuss ... and we said, \'93Well, let\rquote s go then, carrying slogans\'94
. That, for me, was very much ... looking back, an important moment, because it was clear to me then that if the choice came between Jewishness and conformity 
to South Africa on the one hand, and sticking up for certain abstract principles like social justice on the other, I was clearly doing that, and I was very self-aware of it. I think I was probably a bit self-righteous about it, but certainly it seemed to 
