reasingly confused identity ... You know, I felt myself increasingly identifying with a group of people, and a cause, and a set of ideas. I mean, that was very strong, that I was different. And gradually some of these ideas shed themselves off, like the m
ore doctrinaire, Jewish identification the sense that, you know, you had to be quiet and not expose yourself too much. Those ideas I shed, I shed off, and saw myself becoming involved in a wider identity. 
