But, at the same time, I became aware that that id
entity was, itself, a marginal identity, that I would always be on the edge. The more I was drawn to those things, the paradox was that the more I was aware ... that there was a great world out there with the same ideas, and I could identify with those id
eas. I could read about the Spanish Civil War, and I remember being absolutely fascinated about this subject, I was 15, 16, and I just was reading everything, I read Orwell, and I read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Homage to Catalonia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 , and this was just fantastic. So I was aware of this
 sense of being a minute little part of a great world of ideas and commitments, and books, and heroes and heroism ... and social justice. But increasingly, I became aware, as that world expanded, I was also aware that my sense of belonging to this and onl
y this, the total thing was not shared by everybody, to say the least! I don\rquote t know if I\rquote 
m conveying this clearly enough. It was, you know, the sense of the world being there, and therefore, somewhere out there, these ideas running through my head were norm
al; and yet the people who were committed to these ideas, would always remain marginal. And that was, for me, absolutely clear and still is \endash - the more you were universal, the more you would become marginal.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
