And something that struck me was that when I st
arted doing social work, I made friends, in the first year, and stayed friendly with her for all of the four years, was a woman called Mary Dlamini. There were twenty students in the social work group. I was the only male. The B.A. Social Work was definit
ely a woman\rquote s thing, and I was made to be aware of that, that I was doing a woman\rquote s profession. Because I was being sensitive and doing social work. I mean, if I\rquote 
d gone to sociology that would have been okay. But social work was definitely a woman\rquote s thing. 
So I was aware of that. And ... I was the only male ...And the rest were, mainly Jewish, middle-class females. But Mary was the only black. And we formed an identification on that ground, that I was the only male, she was the only black. And we were very 
friendly, within the limitations that I mentioned. You know, we had few social contacts, very little social contact, not on the campus. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
