m just awkward at doing things like that. But there also were two other students, Indian students, Esop and Aziz Pahad, who are both now in the Cabinet. Aziz is Deputy Foreign Minister, and he was one of our group of friends our social group at 
Wits in 1960-1962, and Esop is the Chef de Cabinet, or Administrative Secretary of Thabo Mbeki.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 They\rquote re men?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yeah.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So they weren\rquote t in the social work? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Not in the social work group, but in the social group, yeah. So, you know, I suppose I could talk for a long time, disproportionately long, about university. It was a site, as I say, where much of my political and intellectual self was formed. It wasn
\rquote t so
 much that there were outstanding intellectual people who influenced me, but there was a genuine feeling, for me, that the world of learning and academic world, and ideas, was always where I belonged. So, you know, I was, again, stimulated ... I read, I w
o
uld, you know, just work my way through the reading lists. I would be reading novels, and I would be doing all these things, and doing things which, politically, were probably really rather innocuous, I mean, going to demonstrations and things. But all th
at seemed to be coherent and stimulating, as I say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 You say that there wasn\rquote 
t anybody on the staff that who was an outstanding influence. But who do you think was most influential on the staff?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Hard to say, on a formal level. I can\rquote t think of 
anybody who stood out, on the staff. In political science, if I remember, there were individuals - and English Literature - who represented that link between the world out there, that they\rquote 
d come from places like LSE, or they spoke about London, and they had some connection between the British culture, and yet they were talking about ... very committed to what was happening in South Africa. But I honestly can\rquote 
t think of anybody. I had a sense of collective influence. I don\rquote t think I ever had anyone in particular. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
I think the only exception is ... yes, there is an exception, and she\rquote s the person that I\rquote ve dedicated my current book to.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 States of Denial}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 States of Denial}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, which is about this whole problem of denial, about how we shut things out.
 Stephanie, was a woman who was my supervisor in my casework placement in my last year in social work. My placement was working ... within the Johannesburg Municipality where she worked; she had a small little office there. I was allocated to her by my co
urse supervisor in social work, quite an odd woman, who saw that I would have an affinity with Stephanie.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stephanie?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Her name was Stephanie Breedt }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 her Afrikaans surname}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  but she\rquote 
d been married, briefly, to a Portuguese guy called Bello, and she was sometimes called Stephanie Bello, not as in Saul Bellow, but B E L L O. And she worked in a Johannesburg welfare unit working with vagrant white men. She was the whole unit. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Outside the ... the Municipal Library, in Johannesburg, there was always, what we would now call \'93homeless\'94 people, vagrant, winos, who are known, collectively, in South Africa, by the term, you probably know, \'93poor whites\'94
. And, of course, in South Africa, it was a double statement. If, in a place like South Africa, where the racial exploitation system was so organised, if you were a white and hadn\rquote 
t made it, you know, you were pretty low! And, in addition, if you hadn\rquote t made it, you\rquote d failed and dropped out so badly, that all you were doing was sitting outside the Library, dri
nking, and, you know, pick-pocketing and things like that. And she worked in a - I suppose what we\rquote d call now a \'93rehabilitation unit\'94
, or a kind of hotline. She used to go round and talk to them, and bring them back to the office, and help them with Social Security, and try and get them off drink. So she was just a peripatetic social worker, attached to this office. My placement }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 rather imaginatively by the person who assigned me to her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 , was with Stephanie. And she had a remarkable influence on me, yeah, b
ecause she had something which was new. She represented to me something powerful. She saw that I was a precocious young man, and she was very intelligent, very, very perceptive, and would present me with things as problems, rather than as fixed solutions.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
And one of the problems was the problem ... that I was aware of then, and I\rquote m aware of now, and I\rquote 
ve always written about. How do you think about helping individuals, the humanitarian kind of impulse, but also, at the same time, think of the sociological,
 the Big Things, you know, the structural questions, the social injustices. So what happens, should you go for political work to change the system, or do you deal with individuals and help them in a humanitarian way? And, you know, that is unanswerable. W
e could talk about it, but I think that\rquote 
s a real absolutely important tension, and from Stephanie, I learnt it as a tension. I knew she was committed politically, I knew she was committed to that, individual work. I also learnt from her that you could help 
people, but not be romantic about it. And she used to often talk about, say, bringing one of these, these vagrants, back to her office, and turning around for a minute, and he would disappear with her handbag, and all her money! And once she was stupid en
o
ugh to bring some man home to her flat, and he just took all her possessions. You know, just went through the drawers. And she would continually teach me that, and she was very didactic on that point, and she taught me something which I learnt, and I writ
e about again now which is, you know: to support a cause, or to help people, doesn\rquote t mean you have to actually like them. They might turn out to be rather nasty people! 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
There were many things like that. And she introduced me to so much reading, that I would not have got to. So she, yeah, she was an influential person. And I think, if you even spoke to her you\rquote 
d pick this up. I must suppose, though, that some influence was partly due to the fact that a year afterwards, or shortly afterwards, when I left Sou
th Africa, and was in England, she very tragically killed herself, or fell out of a balcony. Nobody knew what had happened. And in my eyes, that romanticised her status even more.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Were there any other women who were important to you in that period?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I, I don\rquote 
t think so. Nobody, male or female, stands out, except Stephanie, as being, as having an individual influence. You know, I saw groups of people, in the Youth Movement. There were some remarkable people who, who ... well, I always saw these 
people as facilitators, I think. I don\rquote t think I was ever directed ... The people who directed me towards reading were always important for me, but I wouldn\rquote t say that they were influential. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
There was, I remember, a phase, somewhere in 1961/62, where ... Left Bank Existentialism became fashionable, and even though I never smoked }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 and I\rquote ve never been able to smoke, and never understood why people smoke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, it was at the time when we all had to ... everybody smoked Gauloise, or Gitanes, and that was part of the image! And there was a guy, whose name I can\rquote 
t remember, who ran an Existentialism Study Group. And I was aware of a completely different ... I started reading, you know, Sartre, and Dostoyevsky, and Camus, in a kind of popular version. In fact, the popular version that we all were drawn to }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 long before we discovered its proto Fascist side}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  was Colin Wilson. And Colin Wilson looked the outsider. I remember being knocked out by that, and not being able, really, to make any sense of the connection between that and political commitment ... . So I can
\rquote t remember. But, as I say, I would look back and think the guy who ran the study group, Ronnie, as important in my life, because he was the conduit to this; but that didn\rquote t make him influential as a person.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Now, you said this was a turning point, this period was a turning point from your parents. Is it possible to go back now and say something about how your relationship with them changed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 They never solved the problem of their su
spicion, worries, that we would get into trouble. You know, because my brother, at this stage, my younger brother, Robin, who\rquote 
s only two years younger than me, was part of the same network. And when I was in my third year at university, he was probably in 
his first, and so we were together. They were worried that, you know, we would be arrested, and that we were doing these terrible things. And I think our response was really just to develop a secret life, a hidden life, we just wouldn\rquote 
t tell them. And we\rquote d say we were going to a lecture or something like that, rather than say we were going to a party at which there were going to be blacks, because a party with blacks, a \'93mixed party\'94 as it was called in the jargon... 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 That was illegal still, wasn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
The party itself was legal, but drinking was not. So, theoretically, the police could raid, and there were parties where, I remember, people would hide bottles if the police would come. There was one party I do remember where police started sudde
nly appearing, and everybody was putting bottles of alcohol under the floorboards, which I\rquote 
m sure was ... rather transparent! And there were, there were some rather distasteful things at these parties, such as ... black women who had been trapped by the police, possibly on drugs charges, or prostitution... 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11031804\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\ul\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yeah, who\rquote d been trapped, trapped by the police, yes. They used to seduce white activists, and then the policemen would burst in and take a photo, and ... and the guy would be ... might be brought
 on trial, because of the \'93Mixed Marriages\'94 the Immorality Act.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 When was the Immorality Act?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, it was still active then. I\rquote m talking about 1959, 1960
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No, but when were mixed relationships made illegal, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 They were a prod
uct of very early legislation, probably mid-fifties, I would think, or beginning of the fifties. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Anyway, with my parents ... Yeah, I don
\rquote t think we communicated much. We were adolescents and then university students, with worlds of our own. We never did anything that was openly rebellious or deviant, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid11558009 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 
]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 , which would have caused any conflict. I think I just developed a technique of avoiding conflict by concealment, and just living another life.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
