\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No, I don\rquote 
t think I was close. I think I was very over-protected, and very, very much to be Jewish, older kid, the eldest of three brothers. You know, I
 think I got from them, an overdeveloped pathological sense of responsibility, in the sense that everything was always my fault. You know, the classic Jewish joke certainly applied to my life! You know, if we went on a picnic and it rained, I was sure my 
mother thought that it was my fault! So I did get from them a sense of responsibility, that\rquote s for sure, but not, perhaps, in the sense of social responsibility, but a sense that things were my fault. And I suppose, if I\rquote 
m honest, and pushed that line, a lot of the very guilt that I was made to feel, as a child, transferred itself into my sense of guilt and responsibility for the injustices around me. I\rquote m sure ... You know, I\rquote 
ve never thought through that connection in depth, but I\rquote m sure it was there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And when you were tiny, did you have a black nanny?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yeah.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And is she somebody you remembered well, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yes. And that\rquote 
s something which, I actually wanted once to write about it. But I realised that my memories and knowledge were j
ust too obscure to do so. But, of course, yeah, that was something that I think we all must have been aware of. Well, I say we must have been, but again, the problem which I deal with in my book is, some people deny and shut out. But it seems to me, I mus
t
 have sensed, at some level, this impossible tension between this woman who was the source of care, the protector, the one who was looking after me when my mother was away or out for the night, who my mother would leave to look after me, then she would go
 to play bridge that this woman was simultaneously an inferior object, or a non-person. A few South African authors, I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid8349223 think }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid8349223 perhaps}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  Dan Jacobson}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 , could see all this}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 must have written about this. Certainly, Coetzee, in his memories of his childhood, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Boyhood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, which I think is the most wonderful autobiography of being a child/boy ever written. Even though it was of a different period and completely different circumstances from my own, captured a lot of these things about South Africa, about how we felt abou
t them. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Yeah, I guess the woman servant was a clear combination of a love object, who was also a total taboo object. And I think many of us did sense that in some way. But I can\rquote t say that, when I look back and talk about the contradictions, and the whol
e problems of having the servant there, that aspect of it, the emotional aspect of it, was too important. I mean, to me, much more important and striking was the anomaly of age, you know, this man was 40, and I was calling him a boy, and he was calling me
 a master. I suppose I must have been an early sociologist rather than early psychologist, although I think, now, I\rquote 
m more and more drawn back to psychology. So I, you know, it was more in terms of those social hierarchies that I think I sensed the problem.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Now, you mentioned there was a third child, is that a sister, or another brother?
