\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
No, another brother. A third brother, the youngest by two years ... I was the oldest, and then there was Robin, my brother, who was also a sociologist, who was two years younger. And then a third brother. It\rquote 
s interesting because he, just as much as we developed our identity against our parents, and against the dominant system he had to react against }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid8349223 us.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  I think that this is close to what I said earlier, and I always found it striking when I first read Goffman. This was that idea that the structure of society is there in the bricks and mortar \u8722\'2d
 our identity resides in the cracks. And that, to me, was a wonderful idea ... that, you know, that you build the identity }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid8349223 against}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 the institution. And, but I think that tied with what I was saying earlier, that nobody had a positive influence on me, but the environment had a powerful negative influence, in that I was building up my identity against the environment. And I th
ink when, when Robin, my brother, and I, were building up our identities against the dominant political environment, by being involved in the anti-apartheid struggle and so on, my younger brother built up his identity against, against us. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 We both remembe
r him announcing, at a very early age, something about, \'93Well, when I get to university I\rquote m not going to get involved in politics or anything like that, I\rquote m going to just make money, and I want to be a millionaire when I\rquote m 25\'94
, something like that. And, although that\rquote s not exactly what he did, it\rquote 
s pretty close. I remember that he was proud that his own son had done what he had done 25 years later: I think he said the first Society that he joined was the Wine Tasting Society, or something like that. And, ye
s, you know, the notion of identity as negotiated against other identities was very strong. Yet he very much moved with the changes and he stayed in South Africa. He\rquote s never taken an active political line \u8722\'2d he is no racist, and he\rquote 
s very aware of what\rquote s going on.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 What\rquote s his job now, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 He\rquote s in business. I mean, he did what he said he\rquote 
d do. He was not going to ... We saw, very early, that going to university was a route to some kind of, some other intellectual direction. We didn\rquote t, think we 
were going to be academics. I thought I was going to be a social worker, and save the world through some combination of, you know, Mahatma Gandhi and St. Francis on the one hand, and some kind of political identity on the other! I mean, I was struggling w
ith ... we thought going to university was part of that, was learning about the world, in order to do good. Whereas, for him, you know, I think he very clearly thought that going to university was a way to a career, and he went into business.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 What\rquote s he called?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Clive.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So, is there anything more from that university, those university years, you could talk about?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I think I could expand on all of those, because they were such full and den
se years, but I think those are the main things. And I think I came out with so much in my head.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
In my last year at university, I started going out with Ruth, to whom I got married to almost immediately. This is another thing which was so characteristic o
f our generation, was that many of us never had much time, ever living on our own. We would go straight from one family to another, and my case, of course, very similar families ... We started going out as students, and I\rquote 
d known her for years before, thro
ugh the Zionist Youth Movement, and her brother was a friend of my brother, we were in the same neighbourhood, we went to the same synagogue. There was very much the South African middle-class Jewish world, was very powerful in knitting people together fr
om the same background. And most of us did get married to people from the same background, almost automatically, and did so very soon after leaving home. We went straight from leaving our parents\rquote 
 home, to becoming a married couple. So we got married on January 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\super\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 1963, and immediately left South Africa to go to London.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And she was studying what?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
She was studying English Literature. And that was a time, that was a crucial point in our lives, because going ... at that stage we were both clear that going to London was a temporary thing, and we would go for perhaps year, or two years, and ... 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Why were you going at all, though?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, we were ultimately going to Israel. That was ... you see, that is where all these tensions and differ
ent paths lead together in a way which I ... I think I need more than an hour to explain how they come together! 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No, no, take your time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No, no, but I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m up to explaining why ... Well, that was the track. I mean, that was the ma
ster plan, because while we were involved in what was going on in South Africa, we were all sure, our group of people, were all sure of two things. One was that we would leave South Africa as soon as we could, and number two, in our particular group, that
 we would be going to Israel. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
And even though our commitment to the Zionist Youth Movement, itself, might have got a little bit weaker, the commitment to the whole idea was strong. And all this, by the way, has to be understood against Zionism there, comp
ared with American Jewish backgrounds. It would be the only element that would be odd, because I think everything in the culture was similar, but the South African Jewish community was Zionist. To be Jewish there was to be Zionist. You supported the Blue 
B
ox; every Sunday people would come along, and you would give your old clothes, and this would be sold for something in Israel. And there were relatives in Israel you were sending food parcels to, and your identity was very much struck by that. So, for me,
 it was a point where I was ... I think it was ... a moment of, not a moment, but a gradual transition, much uncertainty in which I was not entirely clear. I think that I became aware that you couldn\rquote 
t have it all, all ways. But I would try how far. And we thought, \'93Well, let\rquote s go to London for a half a year, or a year, and see what it\rquote s like, and then go to Israel\'94
. And once we went to Israel, things would become more shut down, you know, that would be it. We would be fulfilling our \'93destiny\'94 as Jews, and Zionists, by going to Israel. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I\rquote 
m exaggerating it slightly, but the idea was, in the meantime, just take off and play around with the other identity, which was universal. And I think that\rquote s where those ... that\rquote s where I think the conflict between the - s
pecialness of being Jewish, or the specialness of any kind of cultural or nationalist identity, struck me as being in contradiction to the universal one. Not as I thought, in a half-baked way at university, where everything seemed manageable ... We hadn
\rquote t thought things through, and I thought, \'93Well, you could do a little bit of each\'94
. I really knew that, you know, that was not possible, that there were elements in universal, and being a person, and in being committed to general ideas of social justice, which were vaguely in contradiction to Zionism. But I\rquote 
d never articulated in this form, and I was still totally na\'efve, and totally indoctrinated by the Zionist Youth Movement. I mean, the amount of lies, and the amount of propaganda we absorbed, was quite astonishing, when I look back.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So it\rquote s much more that you grew up with this idea of going to Jerusalem. It wasn\rquote 
t so much that you were leaving South Africa because you found it politically intolerable, but that it had always been the idea to go to Jerusalem.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 To Israel, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I know, but I\rquote m talking in a metaphorical sense.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Metaphorically, yeah. But no, I wouldn\rquote t say so. I wouldn\rquote 
t say it was rather the one rather than the other, no. I think it was both. It definitely was both. You were conscious of, to put it crudely, you were conscious that if you stayed in South Africa, the theme I talk about in book, there was no way to stay t
here without being aware of the injustices, and doing nothing about them. And if you were not just playing at student politics, but got into the real thing, you\rquote 
d eventually get into prison, and then all the things that our parents said would be right. So, you know, I ... I just don\rquote t think I had the courage ... I mean, if I look back, that\rquote 
s the kind of word I would use. There might be other, less harsh categories, but I didn\rquote t have the courage to face that particular path of total commitment. And I think t
he path of leaving, for many of us, was leaving out of disgust, leaving because you could say, \'93Well, I can\rquote t possibly live in a place like this. You can\rquote t possibly survive in a place as unjust and horrible as South Africa\'94
, so you had to leave. I think that was the stronger push. It was political, but political in the sense of people saying, \'93You can\rquote t live in a place like this without being an activist\'94. And if you were an activist you\rquote 
d get into trouble, and the best thing is to just pack up, to express your disgust by just leaving. But that went along with the sense, yes, that eventually, we would end up in, metaphorically, in Jerusalem.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And were there things about South Africa that you really missed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I\rquote m trying to see wh
ether you felt that you had roots and things that you liked about the country, because, in a way, we\rquote ve been talking about the things you didn\rquote t like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, that\rquote s right. No, I think that\rquote 
s an important point, of course, but at that stage, no. At th
at stage, everything was negative. Everything in South Africa was ... well, was just taken for granted, or negative. I would say that with every year that went by since then, I became more distant. The initial five or six years were like breathing after l
eaving something bad behind I don\rquote 
t think one can exaggerate the sense of which just leaving South Africa and coming to London was a sense of breathing. I mean, Nadime Gordimer, Doris Lessing and Dan Jacobson, and everybody has written about that. And so th
e liberation of just getting out of that place, and leaving it behind, meant that everything about it was negative. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
But in later years, and particularly now, as I sit here, at this point, and after things started unravelling in South Africa, and when you
 saw the prospect of Mandela becoming President ... for me, it went the other way. You know, for me, South Africa has been and became a wondrous place to think of. I so enjoyed going back there in this later period. Unlike Ruth, who had the same experienc
e as me, I think of it as home. If somebody says to me, \'93Free associate \lquote home\rquote \'94, I\rquote ve not the slightest doubt I\rquote d say \'93South Africa\'94
. And I miss it in a deep emotional sense. I miss the commitment, I miss the people ... Although I\rquote m totally an intellectual 
book person, and I hate nature and the countryside and rivers and hills and mountains, you know, they mean absolutely nothing to me. Absolutely nothing to me. I\rquote m a city person, and I\rquote 
ve no feeling at all about physical countryside and so on. But strangely, when I think, when it\rquote s South Africa, it\rquote 
s completely different. I think of the smell in the streets of Johannesburg, and I can think of the sky at night, I remember ... going to Toronto once, and meeting an ex-South African, who I didn\rquote t know to be a So
uth African, Clifford Sheering, who was a sociologist/ criminologist. We met, and we started talking about it, about how much we missed South Africa, and everybody was getting a bit bored! And the host said, \'93
Well, what do you miss most about South Africa?\'94 And almost as if we had rehearsed this, we both said together, \'93The sky\'94
, which, for me, is a totally weird thing to have said, but it is, you know, the black, the totally, the Southern hemisphere sky. At all sorts of levels, yes. And many things about t
he quality of life there, yeah, I miss. But when, but coming to England ... I suppose I should go a bit faster in this narrative, shouldn\rquote t I?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No, no, no, this is perfect.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I\rquote m thinking of running out of time, and ... 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No, we\rquote re fine. We\rquote re not trying to finish it all now, are we!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I\rquote ve suddenly realised I\rquote m going so slowly!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\lang1040\langfe1033\langnp1040\insrsid6313845\charrsid8349223 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang1040\langfe1033\langnp1040\insrsid6313845\charrsid8349223 No, no, no, it\rquote s fine!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I tell you what happened in 
London was, the beginnings of ... look, the beginning of getting a sense of universal, cosmopolitan identity. I think that was crucial. I mean, now, that term, \'93cosmopolitanism\'94
 has been scrutinised a lot, and has come back into fashion. But I think that was it. I mean, the world, the sense that London was the symbol of the world out there, was enormously, enormously reinforced. And London didn\rquote 
t disappoint, it was ... it was all that. I mean, I found the Englishness I didn\rquote t like, the English nationalism.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 The English nationalism? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, the English \'93culture\'94 ... yeah, the English life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 What else about that Englishness didn't you like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, the food, and the physical conditions. I hated the climate. And I found everything dreary 
and dull, physically, you know. Yeah, I didn\rquote 
t like the place, physically, very much. But my sense of London, as another world, well, I remember, my first job. I was then a psychiatric social worker and I looked round for a job as a social worker, and many places wouldn\rquote 
t take me, because my, there was something about the qualification not being recognised, and I needed to study another year.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 You\rquote d just finished your degree and then come?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Absolutely. Yeah, finished the degree, got married, and
 came the next day, virtually. And Ruth started looking for a job as a teacher, and I started looking for a job as a social worker. And the first job, the only place that would take me, turned out to be an absolutely revelatory experience for me, because 
it was, it was cosmopolitanism personified. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
It was a place called the Marlborough Day Hospital, which was a psychiatric hospital, a day-care hospital. The Director was a man called Joshua Bierer, who had been a student of Adler, and for me, this was someh
ow a direct connection with this intellectual world that I\rquote d read about in books, you know. Because I was very bookish kid, always, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 and I still think I\rquote m a bit like that!}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 and the things I read, the things I read, are much more real to me than the things 
I see. I never really believe anything until I read about it. And reading about something is a tangible sense for me, much more tangible than going outside and seeing a tree, or anything like that. And so, here I was, at this Hospital, and the Director of
 
the Hospital was a student of Adler! Now, this, somehow, was fantastic. Not only that, the woman who hired me, the Senior Social Worker, her name was Dorothy Koestler and she turned out indeed to have been married to Arthur Koestler, and to have lived wit
h Koestler in Paris during the Occupation. And there were all these, these resonant echoes. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
But after a year of working there, I then decided that ... there was something about this world of individual social work, which was not for me.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yes. Tell me a bit more about what you were actually doing there, when you were working.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 What was I doing? I was terrified because I didn\rquote 
t know anything about what was happening. This place was a psychiatric hospital, but a mad place also. Bierer hired just a
bout anybody, and everybody was assigned to therapies on what seemed to be on a rather random basis. This was a time when LSD was common as a therapeutic tool, and, you know, there was one doctor there who used to just give his patients LSD. And my role a
s
 a social worker? Well, I was totally ignorant. There were two other social workers, and within about two months of me starting there, I was only 21, one of them got ill, and the other one hurt her leg in a skiing accident, and I was left, and I remember 
her phoning from somewhere in Switzerland and saying, \'93Well, you\rquote ll just have to run the Department!\'94 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 LAUGHS}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  And I was age 21, you know, completely ... surrounded by madness on all sides! And just, you know, I was overwhelmed by this. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Once again, the si
de of being connected with the great tradition, in this case, the psycho-analytical tradition that was very important, but most of the work I was doing, as a social worker, was rather routine work, which I had to learn, of filling in forms, helping people
 with their Social Security Benefits. I did a lot of \'93diagnostic interviews\'94
, as they call them, in the Child Guidance Clinic. And there again, there was somebody with ... you know, these kind of connections that seem to me so important. You know, I was so 
impressed by things like that. That Dorothy had been married to Arthur Koestler then, and Bierer had been a student of Adler. And then it turned out that the Director of the Child Guidance Clinic part, was a guy called Richard Meyer, and Dick Meyer, a won
d
erful man was also very influential on me, and a very interesting person. It turned out that his brother was Michael Meyer, the translator of Ibsen. So there was here another connection with, you know, that other world. And that was, to me, London, you kn
ow, that part of London hit me. But the routine work of the Child Guidance Clinic, of filling out Social Security forms ... not that.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And the other thing I had 
to do most of the time was deal with complaints from the patients, who would come to me and say, \'93Well, why is he getting LSD and I\rquote m not?\'94 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 LAUGHS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  The place was very queer, and I didn\rquote 
t really have a good explanation for any this. I was bewildered by it as much as they were! But, somehow, you try to make sense. And I stayed on, running a Youth Club there, for a couple of years. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
But at that point, I did decide that, that other side of the tension I spoke about earlier, between individual humanitarian helping, one-to-one, and getting some sense of the overall structure. I said, \'93Right, now\rquote s the time to move\'94. \'93I
\rquote ve tried this out, I\rquote ve waited for it\'94. Then I decided I would come to LSE, because LSE, again, was a symbolically significant place. We used to sit at Wit\rquote s reading some issues of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 New Statesman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  that were banned in South Africa. It\rquote 
s astonishing to think of that now, but it was certainly a rather furtive, secret, underground, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 samizdat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  document 
\u8722\'2d the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 New Statesman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 ! At least, that\rquote s the way we made i
t. And so I remember sitting in Johannesburg Library, reading }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 New Statesman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, and reading, at the back, adverts for lectures at the LSE, you know that\rquote s I\rquote d heard about this radical place. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
And anyway, so I applied to the LSE and I came here, and I just ... and I decided I wanted to work on something to do with delinquency. And that\rquote s where I started.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 You applied to do a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid12482122 Ph.D}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yeah. Well, I think I had to do an MA first, or something like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 In sociology?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 In the Sociology Depa
rtment, yeah. I, I was always. The crime/delinquency area seemed a natural one for me, because, on the one hand there were parts about it that came from the correctional, individual tradition of individual pathology and disorganisation, which was still pa
rt of my thinking. And then there was also the notion, that social structure, you know, \'93poverty causes crime\'94
, the great ideas, great simple ideas like that. So all I knew was that I wanted to do something on delinquency. And I came here, and I was told th
at, correctly, that the sociology I had from South Africa was not all that adequate, and I would have to do some qualifying. I think they were called qualifying courses then, I had to do a Master\rquote s Course. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
So I came here to LSE, and, well, it was a combination of being enormously impressed with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 idea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 of being at LSE, which was resonant then, as it is to me now, and the slight disappointment of the reality of it! I mean, in terms of radical politics, it wasn\rquote t quite the radical place that it was held ou
t to be. It never was. It was always, it seems to me, a little ... mythical \u8722\'2d
 not a bad idea anyway. And secondly, in terms of intellectual quality, it was slightly disappointing to me. You know, I went to courses which I had to do, which turned out to be very very boring, and so I was slightly disappointed with that. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
But there were things which were not disappointing. I went to Tom Bottomore\rquote s course on Marxism, and that was interesting \u8722\'2d I found him rather dull as a teacher. Hearing about Marxism was fa
scinating. I was never convinced, and I found myself, at that point, developing a sort of an anarchist consciousness against Marxism, which stayed with me for years. So I never was a Marxist, but ... this was the first time I was hearing somebody who knew
 something ... I listened to him, and to [Ralph] Milliband, and I was very interested in those things. But the person who ... 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So who else was there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, I think I only heard one person who really knocked me out, intellectually, that was Ern
est Gellner. I sensed him as being way superior and I went to a course }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I can\rquote 
t remember what it was called, I think it may have been about Nationalism, already, or culture, or a general course on culture, anthropological course}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 , and being enormously impr
essed. I mean, to me, he seemed in a completely different class, intellectually, compared, say, to Bottomore and Milliband, who I thought were good, but not as striking. I remember other people \u8722\'2d a third class below them \u8722\'2d
 whose names I shouldn\rquote t mention here, who were, who just seemed to be boring. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I had to do courses like the \'93
Social Structure of Modern Britain\'94, which never interested me at all! Because I think I realised then, I was never much interested in factual stuff about the world, but rather in ideas about the world. And I think that\rquote 
s always, that was always true. I didn\rquote t know much about crime and delinquency. I know a lot about ideas about crime and delinquency. So I got attracted to more theoretical courses, but I never was much interested i
n these informative, empirical courses. But I did them. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So Gellner was actually in Sociology at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I believe so. I think he must have been.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And you got to know him at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 No. No, no, I simply went to his lectures. But then, of course, then I started my thesis.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And did you go to any of the Social Policy people, like Titmuss, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 The Department, yes. I didn\rquote t, systematically, because it wasn\rquote t a requirement.
 There were quite a few courses that I had to do, and it was quite tough. There was the Methods Course, and there was the Social Structure Course. And I had to start Criminology, which was, again, that was a very dull course. So I think I had enough. 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Who did you do criminology with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, it was still a man called Eryl Hall-Williams, who\rquote 
s a very nice guy, but a lawyer who taught it in a very pedantic, dull way, which didn\rquote t excite me at all. And my supervisor was Terence Morris, and, well, w
e can have a whole session about him! But he kept up a connection with the sociological tradition about crime. He was a person who, was not easy to have as a supervisor, because what I discovered earlier on about him was that he was almost too encouraging
,
 and I suppose I felt that I needed more individual attention. At this point, I think I was getting very insecure, because I then ... at LSE, unlike at Wits, where I felt I was in control, here I felt that this, this big world, intellectual world, when it
 really started coming, was formidable. And, you know, when I heard somebody like Gellner, that was really something formidable. So I was quite insecure, I needed some encouragement, but Terry gave me almost too much encouragement. He\rquote d say: \'93
Oh, that\rquote s great!\'94 you know ... I didn\rquote t get a lot of guidance. He would just vaguely think and say everything I did was all right. And I needed more guidance and more control ... .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 What was he like, as a person, in those days, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 He was affable and fri
endly as he is now. But as others would confirm, he was a strange mixture. I mean, a complete mixture of different things. He was Catholic, and sometimes he\rquote 
d be a rampant raging Catholic, sometimes elements of anti-Semitism would come into his rhetoric wh
ich you are never supposed to take seriously. Mostly he would be just very, anecdotal. I mean, he told me endless stories. And his lectures were ... seemed to consist of stories and diatribes, and descriptions of what happened to him on the bus. He was a 
magistrate as well, and he was quite punitive. His full name was Terence Morris, and we used to call him \'93Deterrence\'94! Yes, so I wasn\rquote t that thrilled, but, in retrospect, you know, I\rquote 
m grateful to him, he was very encouraging, facilitating, and later, always very kind. But he is a complicated person ... 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
But I think his lack of guidance meant that I was floundering. When I started looking for a subject, I mean, I did it all myself, really, and I was completely ... it was completely overwhelming to me. I decided I would do something on a subject \endash 
 I don\rquote t know how I got connected ... how I got to it \endash  but I decided that the interesting thing about was delinquency was not delinquency, but how people reacted to delinquency. And I hadn\rquote t read labelling theory, o
r anything like that, I hadn\rquote t read much theory at all except the mainstream, which was subcultural theory. Up to that point, sociological theory of delinquency was subcultural theory. And I thought, \'93Well ... \'94
, and I remember writing a proposal for Terry Morris, saying, \'93I want to do something on social reactions to juvenile delinquency\'94, which I think was the title of my thesis. Shall I carry on on this?
