t, nor was I an old-fashioned Liberal, not in the American sense. And it was in Berkeley that I found myself in a similar ... not identical situation. The School of Criminology had broken up under very ugly circumstances, and I could see the case that the
 
radicals were making against the liberals. On the other hand, I could see the case that some liberals were defending, you know, which was some idea of academic freedom. But there were all complicated ideas around at the time. And that was formative for me
