\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Yeah, they call it something different. And there was a guy called, unremarkably, John Smith, who was a lovely old-fashioned man in the old-fashioned WEA tradition in
 the Durham Extra-Mural Department. Someone he knew had contacts with the prison, and he was asked by the prison officers, initially, to run a course for them. And I, I wasn\rquote 
t too keen on this, but John talked me into it, and I thought it might be a good way to find out about prison. And that\rquote s where I started. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
It was a revelation for me. I think it was, like, eight lectures. And I remember, particularly, being struck by a discussion on drugs, which I had with them, on about the fifth or sixth week, in wh
ich they all expressed the most conventional, censorious, anti-drug dealer [views]. And then I had the idea, I don\rquote 
t know why, of going round and asking which of them took things like Valium. They all were! And the work was so stressful, and so ugly, and s
o, this subtly changed the discussion. And, you know, it just opened up. And the other thing that opened things up was, I showed them that Paul Newman movie, you know, the wonderful one called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Cool Hand Luke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 . I don\rquote t know if you know that? It\rquote s a great prison movie, and a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid9847104 great more}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  where Paul Newman is like the rebel against the system, and he eats 50 eggs in a competition. I don\rquote t know if you\rquote 
ve ever seen it ... oh, it\rquote s just a marvellous movie. Absolutely genius. And they loved that. And we used that as a discussion about authority. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
And then, somehow, that led to the project. They\rquote d just opened the E wing, in Durham Prison. The wing was part of what was called the \'93Dispersal Policy\'94, in which they were dispersing some high risk prisoners. These were the
 prisoners, this was after the Great Train Robbery, the Richardson Gang, the Kray Gang, that whole series of rather notorious organised crime or any murders, and the Train Robbery, and they were all put in this special prison. And John Smith, through his 
contacts with the prison officers, if I remember this correctly, I\rquote 
m not sure that I do. John got an invitation from the Governor of the Wing, the Governor who was in charge of the Wing, who turned out to be a very liberal person, a very decent person. Jimm
y G. was his name, and he could already see that the tensions building up in this place, were going to explode. You know, they were all locked up together in this very small regime, with a large number of prison officers watching them, and that they neede
d some break. You know, they weren\rquote t going to get physical breaks, because there was high security, so they weren\rquote t going to get weekend excursions to London! But they could get things like lectures. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
