So he asked John to find somebody in the University. John went to me. And that was the time I was getting friendly with Laurie, and I said to Laurie, \'93This, this sounds interesting\'94. And Laurie met John, and that\rquote 
s how we started. So there was a course on sociology, I think, it was called something almost as boring as \'93Introduction to Sociology\'94! And so we went in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 nearly each week}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, sometimes together, sometimes separately, taking it in turns. But we always used to meet afterwards and talk about it. And we write this history in the book. It was really very muc
h an experience, which was quite formative, very interesting. Looking back, this perhaps meant more, more for Laurie than for me. I think he got much more deeply involved in it, much more deeply involved in it. I think I was always a little bit edgy. We t
aught them, well, you know, the kind of sociology that was around \endash  Berger and Luckman, and that \endash  and that was quite popular. And we talked about drugs, and then we started talking about prison. 
