\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 We started using prison books, and that
\rquote s what really start
ed us off in a subtle conversion of the classes into a research project, because we got them to ... you know, it was a peculiar thing there, Paul. Though they wanted to talk about sociology in general, we were pushing, Goffman and Sykes and the classic wo
r
ks on the sociology of inmate subculture, as a way of sort of testing their reactions. What did they think of what other people had said it was like to be in long-term prison? And some of them were deeply interested in this. But I think most of them were 
m
ore interested in ... things which had nothing to do, and that I can now understand more clearly, I mean, they were more interested in things which had nothing to do with their daily life. I mean, other things to get away with. I think, you know, that is 
the difference which I think we\rquote re all familiar with in other settings. Some people's way of adaptation is to colonise the setting they\rquote re in, by getting to know it very well, getting immersed in it, and others, it\rquote 
s to get away from it. You know that this was actually the tension we then used in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Escape Attempts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, that central idea of structure being made up by the bricks and mortar, and identity being made up by the cracks \endash  the great idea that Goffman uses. And we immediately started teaching them about all
 this, you know. I think it was then that it became even clearer to me that what Goffman was about was not about prisons at all, it was a book about identity, a book about \endash 
 it was a Durkheimian book about the power of the social structure. And that, you know, was much more rewarding teaching these men than it was to ordinary students.
