\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 They did, did understand, intuitively, a lot of what this was about, you know, the prob
lem of insider/outsider, you know. I suppose not so formally in the sense, I mean, they wouldn\rquote 
t write an essay on Weber, but they understood, they had a sociological and a psychological sense of life, they had enormously sophisticated an experience compared to ours. I mean, they\rquote 
ve lived a complicated, devious, deviant, and sometimes rather ugly lives, and they knew what it was like. And you didn\rquote t have to explain to them things like role distance, and concealment, and irony, you know, they knew what those
 things were about. But gradually we tried to push it more and more into them, talking about prison. 
