\'94 summarises the worst of that ideology. Of course, there are things about the personal life which can be understood in political terms, and that\rquote 
s very important. The things about politics which have personal ramifications. But to say that the personal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid11558009 is}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 political, just cuts off, just simplifies things so much, and I think we\rquote d absorbed too much about this integration.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And why is commitment dangerous, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Well, because the underside of commitment is what I came to write about afterwards, in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Denial}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 . The underside is the feeling of self-righteousness and that what you\rquote re doing is be
yond scrutiny. And that people who are not committed, are far inferior human beings. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid11558009 And}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 also that your commitment is in the right commitment. You have to obviously feel that, I mean, you have to somehow feel that, morally, your commitment to a cause - pea
ce, a more decent society, social justice - is, clearly, a more righteous commitment, and that you\rquote ve made a choice and commitment in its strong form, isn\rquote t a kind of Isaiah Berlinish liberalism which you stand for certain things and that
\rquote s it. It was, in a society like Israel, much stronger, it was a very polarised society. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
And so we went there; we decided this with great difficulty, it was a very difficult choice because, really because of the children, because it would mean, really, dislocating them from an environment in which they were quite happy. They didn\rquote 
t express any problems. And they didn\rquote t have these problems, they were my problems and Ruth\rquote s problems. My problems, mainly. And her attraction to be back with her family, her parents and her brot
her, and her sister-in-law she was close to, and nephews. And so quite, it was a difficult decision. We intended to come back, but somewhere in the course of the sabbatical, it\rquote 
s a complicated story, I was offered the possibility of a job there, a more permanent job. We came back here, I think we spent a few months getting ready. I can\rquote 
t quite remember the sequence. We sold the house, and went straight back, and then came into a career, a path of life which was to change my whole life. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
