look at things in England initially as being a little remote ... we were saying, \'93How could we have lived in England all that time? How could we have lived in that place?\'94
 Because we were quite delighted about being in Israel, and about getting these possibilities, and in a way, England seemed a completely and utterly alien place at that stage. I won\rquote 
t go into details, but I just remembered that the Department forwarded me some mail about a year after, or about six months after we left, and one of the letters was a letter from our Vice-Chancellor, Albert Sloman. His office hadn\rquote 
t, obviously, caught up to the fact that I\rquote d left, and it was a letter asking me to, inviting me to come to the Queen\rquote s Garden Party or something, which was something, some ritual tha
t happened every year. And I just looked at this, and I thought, \'93The Queen\rquote s Garden Party! What! How could I even have lived in a society where things like that happened?\'94 Anyway, so I got into Israel.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 So what else about England, at that point, were you particularly glad to have seen the back of?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
Well, I was glad to see the back of the weather! I mean, I was delighted to be in a warm climate, which meant a lot to me. Physically, I loved being out 
there, being able to swim outdoors, not getting dressed up. And I liked the informality of the relationships. I liked being able to pick up on old school friends who had been there, who I hadn\rquote 
t seen for 20 years, and discovered that we still had some language in common. Above all, the weather! It was those three things \endash 
 my sense of commitment and community and integration seemed to be working. I talked myself into that, I think. I mean, that\rquote s the way I look at it now. It seemed to be working. \tab For exampl
e, I think that a major theme in English life, as you know, certainly among the educated middle-classes, and the literate middle-classes, is irony. I mean, irony is the property which you learn here, before you even learn to speak, virtually! And I enjoye
d it at the beginning, but I eventually got tired with English irony. I wondered, when I asked somebody a question about whether they believed in what they told me. I wanted to know whether they believed in it! I didn\rquote 
t want some ironical answer you know! And Israel is a very literal country, which has no irony, and I found that attracted me, at least when stating beliefs, commitment. So I ... shall I just carry on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yes, do. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And I think that worked for a while, in my head. You know, I think the first three years were, I think 
\rquote 79, \rquote 80, by \rquote 81 we\rquote d already bought a flat and committed ourselves, and in that early period things worked because, I think partly because we were so busy just getting settled down, the mechanics there. It\rquote s a difficu
lt society. It\rquote s not at all the kind of Western Ashkenazy Jewish society which dominated our cultural imagery. It is a Levantine, Mediterranean society, where everything is a struggle. \tab 
And so we struggled to get, to find an apartment, and to get involved,
 and not to be ripped off, and to get a phone, and to find a place for the kids for school, and to start learning Hebrew, which was, for me, the biggest challenge. This probably, on the personal level was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 single most important reason}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  for me to give up \u8722\'2d
 just my total inability to master the language, and the frustration that resulted from it. I mean, I did, eventually, lecture in Hebrew, because I was pushed to do so, and my bad Hebrew was still preferable to the students than my good English. So I was 
able to get along. I mean, people said to me, \'93Do you teach in Hebrew?\'94 I said, \'93Well, closer to Hebrew than any other language!\'94
 And certainly it was possible, but I found, every minute I had to spend learning it, I resented, and I also felt outside the s
ociety, at a personal level. So the first two years, I think, were spent, you know, doing what any immigrant does, is integrate and try and absorb, and try and learn, and try and figure out how the place works. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 But gradually, and I think the turning poin
t, politically for me, was the Lebanon War ... At first, Ruth was quite involved, politically ... 
