\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yeah. The first year she was struggling with that, because she didn\rquote 
t have a place where she could se
ll and exhibit, so she was renting from one place to another. But she was working at it, yes. You know, the kids were very unhappy, and most of our time, emotional and actual time, was spent with them, because the schools were not particularly welcoming. 
It\rquote s a hard society, even though they make a lot of noises about absorbing immigrants, the kids had difficulty with the language, it was an alien culture to them, much more rougher, physically. And I hadn\rquote 
t the time, nor had Ruth, really, to do much more than help the children survive ourselves those first two years. But we kept saying, \'93Oh well, it\rquote s okay. It\rquote ll be okay\'94
. People would say that to us. It was a kind of Israeli stereotype, the word in Israel, \'93Yihiye B\rquote seder\'94 which means, \'93It\rquote ll be all right\'94,
 the story was that immigrants would always walk with one shoulder lower than the other, because everybody was touching them and saying, \'93It\rquote ll be all right. Don\rquote t worry, it\rquote ll be okay\'94! So, you know, we believed in that. 

