d work with. But it turned out that their interests were really so far different from mine, their commitment to Israel was so politically different. They would thin
k nothing to invite, senior police to come around all the time. In fact, one of the people in the Institute, I\rquote 
m sure, served as a police informer. Their attitude towards war and the Army, seemed to be absolutely uncritical. And then even before I went, an
other big factor was that I was excluded from the Sociology Department, because Eisenstadt decided that I was, for some reason, I\rquote ve never really discovered not acceptable }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
