In that they were not real students. Again, I might be romanticising, say, the Essex sociology students at the time! But no, I found that the students were, firstly, the culture was anti-intellectual. And, of course, that might have been true here as well
,
 but there were people here who read books. And these criminology students were coming to do an M.Sc., most of them were in the system as probation officers, or police, or prison officers, and, you know, they dragged it out over two or three years. Their 
English wasn\rquote 
t very good. Their English was very poor. They would struggle and resent having anything in English, and obviously, 90 per cent of the literature was in English. And the standards, I thought, were low. I mean, not elsewhere in the University, I
 believe my colleagues in Economics or Mathematics, who said the students were excellent. But certainly not the ones in Criminology! Yeah, I had one or two very nice graduate students who kept me going, but I didn\rquote 
t find the stimulus. And I was still, you know, I would always be writing or phoning, or going to conferences back in Europe or America, and being in touch with my old friends. 
