\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 I think I\rquote 
ve always been interested in the psychological questions. But the question of causation is a different one. I think the simplest way to express it is to talk about this \'93atrocity triangle\'94. There is a tr
iangle ... in one corner there are the victims, to whom things are done, and to whom bad things happen, and they\rquote re the objects of genocide or political massacre, or they become slaves, or whatever. They\rquote re the victim corner. Then there
\rquote s the perpetrator corner, which is dominated by the causal question: \'93Why do people do terrible things?\'94 Where all sorts of interesting questions have been asked. \'93Do they have to believe in what they do?\'94
 Look at the literature on the Holocaust, Goldhagen says, \'93Yes, they did believe them. They were real ideological anti-Semites\'94. Bauman says, you know, \'93No, you\rquote re talking about a victory for modernity. It\rquote 
s something to do with bureaucracy gone mad. It\rquote s nothing to do with belief systems like anti-Semitism\'94. There you have psychological questions, or people say this, \'93Are they authoritarians?\'94 \'93Are they cruel?\'94 \'93
