\'93conscience constituency\'94? That is, their consciences have 
already been pricked by these advertisements, and they do respond. And, not only that, they are attracted to other like-minded humanitarian, or benevolent causes. But are the people who are giving to Amnesty unique in giving to Amnesty, or are they the sa
m
e people who are giving to Oxfam and to Greenpeace? Which is a very intriguing question. And the answer is that there is a large overlap. I interviewed somebody who was a marketing manager for one of the big charities, and he approached everything through
 rational choice theory. And his argument was that people gave because the satisfaction lay in market value. If you want to buy cheap jeans, you don\rquote 
t get much satisfaction, but if you buy brand name jeans, you get satisfaction, so you ask more money for them. He said some silly things like that. But he also said: \'93Some people want a balanced portfolio\'94
, you know, so they buy a third into the environment, and a third into Human Rights, and a third into poverty. But you\rquote re absolutely right, and a host of those questions lay beyond me. 
