\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Yes, yes. They select the \'93right\'94 photos. Here\rquote 
s an interesting methodological digression, which I hope is not too much of a digression. The media person at the one organisation showed me a plate of a hundred photos, and he said, \'93We\rquote re going to choose one of these to put in the advert\'94
, and he said, \'93What do you see in common?\'94 There was a hundred children, black African children\rquote s faces. And I couldn\rquote t see what he was getting at. And he said, \'93Well, just look. Keep looking. You\rquote ll see something ... \'94
 and I looked for ten minutes, and I just ... he said, \'93Can\rquote t you see, not a single one of them is smiling? We cut out all the smiling\'94. Now, you know, even under the most adverse conditions, if you go to a village, some kids laugh. They
\rquote re playing games, even if they\rquote re in a bad condition. They often laugh, they often smile. That had to be cut out, because that is incongruent with the message of total dependency. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 And he said, \'93Look at something else\'94
. He showed me another lot of photos, of children standing. And he said, \'93What do you notice about that?\'94 And again, I couldn\rquote t ... and he said, \'93Well, they\rquote re all alone\'94. He said, \'93Kids aren\rquote 
t always just standing in the middle of their village alone, they\rquote ve often got a mother or a brother, or somebody holding an arm around them, or they\rquote re holding hands. These were cut out\'94. So, you know, here\rquote s the \'93
politics of representation\'94. I think, actually, the whole field of cultural studies and media representation has got a lot to answer for, because they\rquote ve over- emphasised the problem of representation, which is, \'93How do you depict poverty?
\'94 or \'93How do conceptions of colonialism come into this text?\'94 
