s thinking and verbalisation and emotional processes. You don\rquote t just say, \'93Oh, he\rquote s indifferent\'94, and that\rquote s it. Or, \'93She\rquote s moved\'94, and that\rquote s it. The question is, what do you do with your indi
fference? People don\rquote t just have emotions, like having an epileptic fit, they reflect on their emotions. Emotions are framed and judged; people say, \'93I feel guilty, but I shouldn\rquote t be feeling guilty\'94
. The debate between guilt and shame is one like that. You know, you can feel proud of being guilty, but you can\rquote 
t feel proud of being ashamed. And perhaps shame is a better emotion. And no doubt the politically correct version of some of these problems is intellectually correct, that the source of poverty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 [}{
