fication, and what they wanted was greater complexity. This is important: in thinking about the role of information. Now, is it necessarily true that if you provide more complex information, people will react differently, or better? And the limited amount
 of research there is runs against that. Some research on blood donation shows, very clearly, that sympathy works less than empowerment. People want what is called, \'93Pathways to help\'94
. This is characteristic in the classic bystander situation, you see somebody being attacked in the street and the fact that you don\rquote t do anything about it, we know derives from several things. For example, that you feel that you\rquote 
re just one among many. So \'93Why me? Somebody else can do it\'94. And so the larger the group, the less 
likely you are to intervene. You also have to be able to identify with the victim as being part of your group. And so the question is, where do the moral boundaries of society get drawn? But thirdly, you have to have an avenue of help, a pathway. You have
 to have empowerment. You have to know what to do. And in some cases, it\rquote s pretty obvious what to do. But it\rquote s not always so obvious. And the people in this focus group, say, \'93
Well, yeah, I feel outraged at the thought of these pictures of the mass rape of women in Bosnia, but how can giving \'a310 to Amnesty solve that problem?\'94
