m always going back to that question}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid11558009 ]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
 that made her know from that moment that she would never be able to keep that sight out of her mind. She said she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid11558009 knew}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
, and I believe, I absolutely believe her. At that moment, or the year afterwards, two things became clear to her. One was that this was stuff she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242  to do, and remember, of course, in the study of altruists, there\rquote s often a sense of compulsion. \'93How could I not do it? If I didn\rquote t help I\rquote d be false to the kind of person that I think I am\'94
, which is very important. So that is the number one. And the number two: \'93I realised that I couldn\rquote t do everything\'94, which might sound obvious, but is a most important point, that these are not people who think, \'93
Ah, I must run off to East Timor\'94, or \'93I must give money to save the rain forest\'94, they\rquote re not like that, they\rquote re people who still select their causes, and are realistic. And you know, I haven\rquote t got hard data, but I\rquote ve
 
talked intensively about this with a large group of people who belong to this international human rights world, but also do local work. In this group we have people from India, and from Sri Lanka, and from all of Latin America, and I cannot think of one o
f, say, this group of 25, I cannot think of one of them who correspond to the bleeding heart liberal stereotype. 
