\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 Stan:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 How have I changed? I have become more radical, in all senses of the word. I\rquote m less busy lookin
g over my shoulder about what people will think, and I\rquote m less trying to find a \'93balanced\'94 position. I am more attracted to people like Chomsky \u8722\'2d who\rquote s always been an intellectual hero of mine \u8722\'2d
 who does simplify the world, but I think, actually, has got the right message. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
And another influence over me is Nils Christie, who\rquote s been a close friend for 30 years. And, you know, he says some things which are \'93extreme\'94 about criminal justice systems, and about deprofessionalisation, but I think, basically, he\rquote 
s right, you know. And I\rquote ve become more radical beyond the sense that I think that, the general sense of the word, \'93radical\'94
 as applying to political life. My attitude to religion, for example, was always, either indifference or just irritation. Whereas now I\rquote m plain hostile! I just won\rquote 
t have anything to do with it. You know, I just will not go into a synagogue. And one of my causes in Israel, at the end of my stay there was the Secular Burial Society. I signed out: they didn\rquote t get me while they\rquote re alive, an
d I'd rather they don't get me while I\rquote m dead. I\rquote ve become bitterly anti-religious, you know.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\sa200\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10315610\contextualspace {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid6313845\charrsid13831242 
